<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 93 / Electricity price controls accepted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL 12 regional electricity companies in England and Wales have accepted a
new set of price controls which provide incentives for energy saving in
their supply businesses, Michael Smith writes.
Offer, the industry regulator which proposed the revised regime, said
yesterday that the controls will also require companies to make and pass on
further efficiency gains to customers. Acceptance of controls covering the
supply businesses clears the way for talks on how the more lucrative
distribution arms of the businesses should be regulated.
The supply businesses, which buy power from the generators, account for
about 10 per cent of the regional companies' profits. From next April
revenue rises will be limited to the rate of inflation minus 2 per cent. At
present the companies can raise prices in line with inflation.
</TEXT>
