<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 93 / Salvation Army probe widens
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JIMMY BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRAUD SQUAD detectives have flown to Luxembourg as part of a continuing
investigation into a Pounds 6.2m alleged fraud against the Salvation Army,
the world's largest voluntary organisation.
Detectives are understood to be seeking details of Pounds 4m missing from
the charity's funds which were supposed to be frozen in a Luxembourg bank
account.
It is thought that the police investigation has made little progress since
it arrested and subsequently bailed Mr Stuart Ford, a Birmingham businessman
alleged, in a civil action brought by the Salvation Army, to be at the
centre of the fraud. Mr Ford denies any wrongdoing.
The Salvation Army said yesterday that it remained determined to do
everything possible to recover the missing funds, but was in the meantime
being forced to reorganise its internal funding arrangements to deal with
the anticipated shortfall in its accounts.
Profits generated by Reliance, the Salvation Army in-house bank, by Sagic,
the charity's insurance arm, and by Salvation Army Publishing and Supplies,
are to be used more directly in supporting social projects.
The reorganisation of the charity's internal funding arrangements was
ordered by the Salvation Army's board of trustees, which is chaired by
Commissioner Dinsdale Pender.
The Charity Commission meanwhile said that it was continuing its
investigation of the affair, although the Salvation Army believes a final
report will not be ready until early next year.
In April the charity dismissed one of its top officials, and moved three
others to new jobs at the end of its own internal investigation into the
alleged fraud. It said there was no suspicion of dishonesty by any of the
disciplined people.
</TEXT>
