<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 93 / OFT wants credit trade deregulated
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM KING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUBSTANTIAL deregulation of the marketing of consumer credit is suggested by
the Office of Fair Trading in a discussion document published yesterday.
The OFT also suggests deregulating credit agreements and lifting some of the
criminal law's sanctions against the credit industry. The document is part
of the OFT's review of the 1974 Consumer Credit Act, requested by the
Department of Trade and Industry under the government's deregulation
initiative.
Mr John Mills, OFT director of consumer affairs, said yesterday that he
wanted to explore the scope for greater self-regulation by the credit
industry.
The Consumers' Association expressed concern over the proposals 'given the
track record of self-regulation' in the financial services sector.
The OFT stresses that protection of consumers is paramount but says that the
act and its regulations - which govern credit agreements up to Pounds 15,000
 -might be imposing greater burdens on providers of credit than are
necessary for effective consumer protection.
It says the current system of licensing credit providers is not up for
review, but the OFT is considering setting tougher conditions for the
granting and retaining of licences, while relaxing detailed regulations.
The discussion document invites comment on specific areas where the OFT
believes regulations might be cut.
It has asked for comment on whether the detailed regulations on credit
advertising deliver high standards in practice and suggests that credit
advertisements could be subject to self-regulation by the Advertising
Standards Authority or a similar body.
The OFT also questions the effectiveness of 'health warnings' in credit
advertisements - such as the requirement for mortgage adverts to warn of the
danger of loss of the home if payments are not kept up.
It invites local authorities and trading standards officers to estimate the
cost of enforcing the credit act and asks whether criminal sanctions are the
appropriate way of enforcing the rules.
The OFT says deregulation would reduce costs for the lending organisations.
The Consumers' Association said the OFT's thinking was weighted too heavily
in favour of lenders.
Ms Jean Eaglesham, head of money policy at the association, said: 'All our
research and evidence suggests that much tighter control of marketing is
needed.'
She added that the OFT was wrong to rely on the licensing system which is
not an effective policing mechanism.
The Consumer Credit Act prescribes a range of monetary limits for which the
act's provisions apply. The OFT suggests that the limits - which were last
revised in 1982 - should be reviewed so that the act applies to credit
agreements up to Pounds 30,000.
Lending and hiring to business customers is not discussed in the
consultation document, although the government's deregulation task forces
have suggested removing such agreements from the act. The OFT has advised
the government against such a course and plans to publish a discussion
document in the autumn on the treatment of business customers under the act.
The deadline for responses to the document is October 20. Public hearings
will be held in London on October 27-28 and in Leeds on November 2.
Consultation Document on the Working and Enforcement of the Consumer Credit
Act 1974. Office of Fair Trading. 081 398 3405.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
