<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 93 / Howard announces plans to ease betting shop curbs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP RAWSTORNE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HIGH STREET betting shops are to be given a facelift under government
proposals published yesterday.
Bookmakers will be allowed window displays featuring top bets and television
sets showing racing and other sports action.
Inside the shops they will be allowed to increase the size of TV screens and
provide more light refreshments. The ban on alcohol will con-tinue.
Present regulations require that windows must be obscured to prevent
passers-by catching a glimpse of tele-vised horse-races and bet-ting shows.
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, launching a consultative paper yesterday
on the relaxation of the restrictions, said: 'The veil over betting shops
could soon be lifted. The changes would make betting offices a more visible
part of the high street scene and enable bookmakers to provide additional
information about their business.'
Mr Howard said the intention was to give con-sumers more freedom while
ensuring fair and honest betting. He said: 'Care would be taken to ensure
that these changes do not result in betting shops becoming general
entertainment centres.'
The moves, which follow the easing of restrictions on evening opening
earlier this year, were welcomed by the industry.
Mr Kelvin Stacey, marketing director of Coral, said: 'We have been
up-grading our shops for some time and these changes will enable us to move
further forward. They would put us on a normal retail footing.'
Mr John Brown, managing director of William Hill, said: 'Now we can show
betting shops are no longer smoky dens.'
</TEXT>
