<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 93 / Policemen jailed for King beating
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LOS ANGELES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TWO police officers convicted of violating the civil rights of Mr Rodney
King, a black motorist whose beating in 1991 by the men was captured on
videotape, were sentenced to 30 months' imprisonment yesterday, Reuter
reports from Los Angeles.
District Judge John Davies imposed the prison terms on Sergeant Stacey Koon
and Officer Laurence Powell after nearly four hours of arguments by
prosecutors and defence lawyers. Koon, who directed the beating, and Powell,
who delivered most of the baton blows, could have received prison terms of
up to 10 years. The judge said he chose a lesser sentence because of the
resistance put up by Mr King during his arrest and the negative impact on
the police officers' lives from the notoriety of the case.
The acquittal of the two men, and two other police officers, on most charges
in a state court in April, 1992, sparked three days of rioting in Los
Angeles.
</TEXT>
