<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 93 / Clinton puts his faith in the Senate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROGER MATTHEWS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT Bill Clinton took the battle to win approval for his budget
proposals to Capitol Hill yesterday, declaring: 'I do not think the Senate
will let this plan go down. I do not think they will do that to the
country.'
The House of Representatives is due to vote on the compromise budget package
today, with the more finely balanced Senate vote due on Friday. Under the
compromise worked out by Congress the budget deficit will be reduced by
Dollars 496bn (Pounds 332.8bn) over the next five years, achieved by raising
more than Dollars 243bn in new taxes and cutting about Dollars 253bn in
spending.
Asked if he would win, the president would only say: 'I hope so'.
Mr Al Gore, the vice-president whose casting vote was needed to get the
original budget bill through the Senate, said yesterday he did not know
whether he would decide the fate of the legislation again tomorrow. 'But one
way or another, this bill is going through,' he added.
To blunt Republican criticism that higher income tax charges for the
country's top earners were being made retroactive to January 1, a Treasury
official said yesterday the back payments could be made in three tranches.
The concession, which has been written into the amended bill, would allow
the additional amounts for the current fiscal year to be paid on April 15
next year and on the same date in the two succeeding years.
Mr Bob Dole, the Republican leader in the Senate, has accused the
administration of imposing the biggest tax increase in history. He also
claims that Mr Clinton and his fellow Democrats are so anxious to get their
hands on the public's money 'that they made the tax increases retroactive. .
. to 20 days before President Clinton got to the White House'.
The latest public opinion polls underline the difficulty faced by the
Democrats in persuading the public that the new income tax charges are fair
and only fall on the highest earners. According to a USA Today/CNN/Gallup
poll, about 68 per cent of respondents believed that middle-income taxpayers
would shoulder most of the additional burden.
Democratic Senator Dennis DeConcini of Arizona, who party leaders are
pressing hard to swing his vote in favour of the legislation, continued to
tantalise yesterday. Having voted previously against the bill, he said he
was still leaning in that direction.
</TEXT>
