<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 93 / Kurd rebels kill 20 in Turkey
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ISTANBUL
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
KURDISH guerrillas stopped two minibuses travelling in the south-east of
Turkey yesterday and gunned down about 20 civilian passengers and wounded 10
others, agencies report from Istanbul.
Gunmen of the Kurdistan Workers Party (PKK) stopped the minibuses near
Bitlis in south-east Turkey and forced all of the estimated 30 passengers
out of the bus and shot them, according to the semi-official Anatolian news
agency.
It said the wounded were flown to the town's state hospital by helicopters.
Earlier, Turkish officials said a PKK rocket attack killed eight soldiers
and two state-paid village guards at a military post near Yuksekova in
Hakkari province, near the Iranian border, on Tuesday night.
Two other soldiers and three village guards were badly wounded in the
attack. More than 6,550 people have been killed in Turkey since the PKK
began its fight for an independent Kurdish state in 1984.
