<HEADLINE>
FT  05 AUG 93 / Treasury chief hits back at department's detractors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR Terry Burns, the top civil servant at the Treasury, has strongly
defended the department against critics who accuse it of policy failures
such as sterling's departure from the European exchange rate mechanism and
the decline of manufacturing industry, writes John Willman.
In an article released today, Sir Terry says that much of the criticism
arises from the Treasury's privileged position at the heart of Whitehall,
which makes it an easy target when things go wrong.
Too little credit has been given, he says, for changes made where the
Treasury has acknowledged criticism as well-founded.
Sir Terry concedes that there are arguments for an independent Bank of
England to handle monetary policy, including 'weak' evidence that inflation
is lower in countries with central bank independence.
The demand for greater independence of the central bank is, he says, 'the
most popular single answer to the problem of inflation that was once
reserved for the ERM'.
Scapegoat butts back, Page 14
Observer, Page 15
</TEXT>
