FT  04 AUG 93 / (CORRECTED) World Trade News: ABB wins Athens airport
contract
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Correction (published 13th August 1993) appended to this article.
A consortium led by Mannheim-based ABB Schaltanlagen, part of Asea Brown
Boveri, has won a Dollars 420m (Pounds 282m) contract to provide and install
all the electrical equipment for the new Athens airport at Sparta, writes
Andrew Baxter.
The contract from the Greek government follows last week's selection of a
consortium led by Hochtief, the German construction company, to build the
airport. The complete project is worth about Dollars 2.3bn. ABB companies
are partners in the overall consortium, and will account for about Dollars
235m of the electrical work won by the subsidiary consortium.
CORRECTION
In the Financial Times of August 4, a contract for a new airport near Athens
was recorded as being at Sparta. It should have read Spata.
