<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / London Stock Exchange: Waters easier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and ZHANG TINGTING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Water issues weakened, dragging down some regional electricity companies
with them, as at least two brokers decided that the sector looked
overvalued. BZW struck a cautious note in its latest piece of research,
advising clients to move 'underweight' in the water sector, as it
highlighted potential regulatory dangers likely to be thrown up when Ofwat
makes its next report in the autumn.
BZW suggests that should the regulator adopt a similar view on capital
values to those taken by other regulatory bodies then the water stocks will
look expensive. With their recent post-ERM gains, BZW believes they could be
around 13 per cent overvalued at current values. Ms Angela Whelan, utilities
analyst at BZW, said: 'This represents an excellent opportunity to sell into
strength and realise profits.'
NatWest Securities was also underlining regulatory worries in retaining its
'neutral' stance, suggesting that this month's Ofgas report on British Gas
will have direct implications for how Ofwat decides to act on its sector.
The broker also said that the sector was looking overbought at its morning
meeting. Among those stocks hit, Anglian slipped 5 to 497p, Southern 6 to
525p and Welsh 4 to 584p.
</TEXT>
