<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / NatWest gains on relief of bad debt in south
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NATIONAL Westminster Bank yesterday disclosed a sharp fall in provisions
against bad and doubtful debts in the first half of the year as the recovery
in the economy started to relieve bad debt in the south of England.
NatWest's bad debt provisions of Pounds 641m were 23 per cent down on the
Pounds 828m charged in the same period last year, and 36 per cent down on
the Pounds 995m provision in the second half. New provisions fell by the
largest percentage in the south.
The bank's pre-tax profits rose to Pounds 421m, against Pounds 211m, despite
making an exceptional Pounds 159m provision against its decision to pull out
of retail banking in France and Australia. It expects to recover little of a
Pounds 135m investment in France.
The most profitable sector was NatWest's corporate banking and securities
arm, NatWest Markets. It made pre-tax profits of Pounds 253m, up from Pounds
141m, helped by dealing profits of Pounds 246m. These were boosted by
currency trading in volatile conditions.
The UK retail branch business returned to a profit of Pounds 69m, compared
with a Pounds 74m loss, as provisions fell from Pounds 609m to Pounds 442m.
But branch banking profit before provisions slipped to Pounds 511m, against
Pounds 535m, because of what the bank described as weak demand for loans due
to lack of confidence.
Lord Alexander, chairman, said the recession had dominated results for three
years, but the economic background was now 'improving, albeit modestly and
patchily'. The provisions fall was welcome, but bad debts remained
unacceptably high.
The bank raised its interim dividend by 4.5 per cent to 6.4p after earnings
per share went up from 8p to 12p. Lord Alexander said it was strongly
capitalised and had 'no current plans' for a rights issue.
Mr Derek Wanless, chief executive, said there had been a lack of demand for
all forms of lending except mortgages. Lending in the branch network fell by
Pounds 2.1bn, although UK mortgages rose by Pounds 1.2bn to Pounds 10.2bn.
Mr Wanless said the bank would be 'disappointed' if provisions did not fall
further by the end of the year, but it could not be confident about the size
of the fall. The bank believed that the recovery was established but it
remained fragile.
The bank's net interest margin on loans fell from 3.2 to 2.8 per cent
because it took on lower margin assets in treasury operations. The fall in
base rates narrowed the gap between variable rate lending and retail
savings.
Non-interest income rose by 14 per cent to Pounds 1.6bn, taking it to 46 per
cent of total operating income of Pounds 3.45bn, against Pounds 3.17bn.
However, costs including exchange rate movements rose by 4 per cent to
Pounds 2.23bn.
The bank's new life insurance subsidiary, NatWest Life, contributed Pounds
21m to profits, while the mortgage operation, National Westminster Home
Loans, increased pre-tax profits from Pounds 20m to Pounds 59m helped by
asset growth and wider margins.
The bank's ratio of core tier 1 capital to risk-weighted assets stayed at
5.5 per cent, although it rose from 5.2 per cent at the end of 1992, helped
by a Dollars 250m preference share issue and a Pounds 1.4bn fall in
risk-weighted assets.
The shares gained 13p to 510p.
Lex, Page 14; Details, Page 16
</TEXT>
