<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / Heavy truck decision angers pressure groups and industry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE FREIGHT transport industry and environmentalists yesterday attacked from
separate flanks a government decision allowing the use of 44-tonne lorries
on journeys to and from UK rail freight terminals.
Regulations to be introduced in the autumn will allow the heavier lorries on
such routes, provided that they are six-axle vehicles which spread loads
evenly. The present limits are 38 tonnes for articulated lorries and 35
tonnes for lorries pulling trailers.
Mr John MacGregor, transport secretary, said the heavier vehicles would be
no bigger and cause no more wear to roads than existing vehicles. He
predicted that the measure, combined with other incentives to move goods by
rail, would reverse the long-term decline in rail freight.
However, the decision was immediately attacked as a missed opportunity to
raise the weight limits for all lorries on Britain's roads. The
Confederation of British Industry said that allowing 44-tonne trucks more
generally would have enhanced the competitiveness of British business.
The Freight Transport Association said that lifting the limit for all
lorries to 44 tonnes would reduce the number of lorries on the road and save
industry Pounds 300m in transport costs.
The shipping industry complained that the restrictions would remain on
lorries using ferries. Sir Nicholas Hunt, director-general of the Chamber of
Shipping, described shipping as 'the transport mode most friendly to the
environment'.
Environmental pressure groups said the decision was unlikely to reverse the
decline of rail freight. Mr Tony Burton of the Council for the Protection of
Rural England said that, without close enforcement of the routes, it would
increase the number of lorries in villages and on country roads.
The change in rules is intended to encourage industry to send more container
freight by rail, according to Mr MacGregor. Existing lorry weight limits do
not allow containers to be loaded to their maximum capacity.
Mr Garry Turvey, director-general of the Freight Transport Association, said
that the government had chosen an option with the least benefits to
industry, the environment and the economy.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
