<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Gunsmoke began in the US on CBS Radio in 1952 with William Conrad (now best
known as 'Cannon' the fat detective) playing Marshal Matt Dillon. When CBS
decided on a TV version they asked John Wayne to play the part but, not
wanting to commit himself to a weekly television series, Wayne suggested a
relatively unknown young friend for the role: James Arness. The first TV
episode was screened in 1955 and Arness, even taller than his mentor at 6 ft
7 ins, went on to make hundreds of episodes: there were 512 before the show
ended in 1975, by which time it had inspired and outlasted dozens of other
Western series. On BBC2 at 6.50 Arness stars in the episode 'Gunfighter,
RIP'.
Reporting from Zambia, On The Line (8.30 BBC2) considers the position of the
World Cup squad in a soccer-mad nation whose national team was killed in an
air crash in April. Radio 4 begins a series called Accidents Will Happen
which looks at the more metaphysical aspects of seemingly haphazard events:
coincidences of the sort which most people have experienced and so many feel
to have been more than mere chance (8.45).
</TEXT>
