<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / AEEU merger talks with Ucatt stoke union rivalry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE EXECUTIVE council of the AEEU engineering and electrical union agreed
yesterday to seek merger talks with the ailing Ucatt construction union.
The move will intensify inter-union rivalry in the construction industry
because two other unions - the TGWU general union and the MSF white-collar
union - are also trying to interest Ucatt in an amalgamation.
Although the 200,000 member Ucatt has severe financial problems and a
dwindling membership in an industry where non-unionism is widespread and
unemployment acute, it is regarded by other unions as a strategic asset as
they fight a rearguard action for members and influence.
Mr Bill Jordan, AEEU president, said yesterday: 'A merger between our two
unions would create a formidable force in the construction industry.'
Ucatt's executive has agreed to meet the AEEU to discuss a possible merger
but in a statement yesterday it pointed out the difficulties of such a
development.
The AEEU contains a construction and building trades section which includes
some members that the construction union says were poached from it by the
EETPU electricians' union before its amalgamation with the AEU last year.
The Ucatt executive said yesterday that the 'continued existence of the
construction and building section remained a formidable obstacle to
productive discussions'.
The Ucatt leadership is embroiled in a serious row with the AEEU over the
issue.
Mr George Brumwell, Ucatt general secretary, said last night that the AEEU
continued to persist in its poaching activities in the building and civil
engineering industries. He added that this issue remained a 'barrier to the
AEEU electricians' section's reaffiliation to the TUC (Trades Union
Congress)'. The electricians were expelled from the TUC in 1989 for
breaching its rules on poaching of members, but delicate diplomacy is being
tried to smooth their peaceful return to the TUC at next month's congress.
Mr Brumwell warned yesterday that the TUC conciliators had not resolved the
problems of the reaffiliation of the AEEU's electricians' section in a way
which would be acceptable to other TUC unions.
</TEXT>
