<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / 110,000 more building jobs forecast to go
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FURTHER 110,000 construction jobs could be lost before employment in the
industry picks up in 1995, the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors said
yesterday in a gloomy assessment of the industry's prospects.
Quantity surveyors' workload is continuing to fall in spite of signs earlier
this year that levels were beginning to stabilise, the institution's latest
statistics show.
During the past quarter the workload has fallen by 1.5 per cent compared
with 0.7 per cent in the previous quarter. Workload is down by 10 per cent
over the past 12 months.
Mr Christopher Vickers, the institution's construction spokesman, said:
'These figures are very disappointing. They show little improvement in
construction activity for at least the next six to nine months . . . It
appears earlier hopes that a recovery was under way were premature.'
The institute's forecast of a further 110,000 job losses comes on top of the
300,000-plus jobs already shed by the construction industry in the current
recession. Employment was about 1.35m at the end of last year.
Mr Vickers said that although more people were considering building, few
were committing themselves.
He said: 'A return in confidence is desperately needed if these projects are
to get past the initial feasibility stage.'
The institute's forecast is gloomier in tone than the one from the Council
of Building Material Producers on Monday. That predicted an upturn for the
industry in the second half of this year, but only if public-sector spending
was maintained.
Sir Alan Cockshaw, the chairman of the construction group AMEC, agreed with
the institution's figures, 'which do suggest there is little hope of any
apparent recovery this year or, indeed, before 1995'.
But he warned against 'interpreting these figures across the totality of UK
construction, as there are areas of the industry where prospects are far
more positive, such as process and civil engineering'.
</TEXT>
