<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / Council accused of 'social cleansing'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday criticised the Audit Commission for the delay in publishing
its report on alleged abuses of housing policy by the
Conservative-controlled Westminster City Council.
Mr Jack Straw, Labour's local government spokesman, published a report which
alleged that Westminster had indulged in 'gerrymandering' and 'social
cleansing'.
He said it was being published now because of Labour's concern over the
length of time the investigation of Westminster by the district auditor has
taken. It started in 1989.
Mr Andrew Foster, the controller of the Audit Commission, had told Mr Straw
that the auditor's report would be published in July. It is not now due to
appear until October.
The auditor told Labour in a letter that his investigation had been delayed
by his discovery that council documents had been shredded.
Labour's report alleges that Westminster designated council houses for sale
in electorally marginal wards. The report says this was done because people
buying houses were more likely to vote Conservative than council tenants.
It also accuses Westminster of 'social cleansing' by placing homeless people
in developments outside the borough. The council says this policy was
adopted to avoid Westminster's high property prices.
The council asserts that it guarantees homes to residents established in the
borough.
