<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / Bright outlook for work in Scotland
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
UNEMPLOYMENT in Scotland should continue to be lower than for the UK as a
whole for the rest of this year and for 1994, although Scotland's rate of
economic growth is likely to fall behind that of the UK.
This is the view of the Scottish Economic Bulletin, a Scottish Office
publication, which bases its opinion on the consensus of independent
economic forecasters.
Scotland's unemployment rate has been below that of the UK since January
last year, a situation believed to be unprecedented since the 1920s. In June
this year Scottish seasonally adjusted unemployment was 9.6 per cent
compared with the UK rate of 10.4 per cent, and was lower than that of all
UK regions except East Anglia and the east Midlands.
The bulletin says that the relatively low rate of unemployment in Scotland
reflects the severity of the recession in the south of England compared with
the northern regions, including Scotland.
It says that all independent forecasters except Cambridge Econometrics
expect Scottish GDP growth to be equal to or below the UK's this year and in
1994.
They expect the south of England to recover from recession faster than
Scotland as the fall in house prices ends, while Scotland may also be
affected by a drop in North Sea oil investment.
Scottish Economic Bulletin. HMSO. Pounds 11.50.
</TEXT>
