<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / Finance shake-up urged for businesses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FUNDAMENTAL rethink of the way small, growing businesses are financed was
urged yesterday by Mr Howard Davies, director-general of the Confederation
of British Industry.
Speaking at the launch of a report by the CBI's Smaller Firms Council, he
urged the development of alternatives to the bank overdraft. In the UK
overdrafts account for 58 per cent of total business debt, compared with 35
per cent in Italy and just 14 per cent in Germany.
One of the report's recommendations is for the creation of a smaller
companies' investment network to replace the business expansion scheme which
ends in December. The network would consist of wealthy private individuals -
'business angels' - willing to provide equity backing for local businesses,
local investment funds and investment brokers.
The individuals could either invest directly or spread their risk by
investing through a smaller companies' investment fund. The investment
brokers would match business angels with suitable companies or draw on the
local investment fund to back eligible smaller companies.
Business angels should be eligible for tax relief on their investments of up
to Pounds 250,000 a year compared with the Pounds 40,000 relief currently
available under the BES, the CBI says.
The report also calls for more generous capital allowances on investment in
plant and machinery to cover 100 per cent of the first Pounds 200,000 spent.
Finance for Growth. CBI Publication Sales, Centre Point, 103 New Oxford
Street, London WC1A 1DU. Pounds 10.
</TEXT>
