<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / Pension concerns prompt SIB review
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SECURITIES and Investments Board, the City's chief watchdog, yesterday
issued a consultative document on the regulation of custodial companies,
which hold the share certificates of investors for safekeeping.
The SIB review was prompted by the theft of more than Pounds 440m from
pension funds controlled by the late Robert Maxwell, in which the role of
the custodians has been called into question.
The consultative document says 'the case for making the provision of custody
services an authorised activity (under the Financial Services Act) has not
yet been made'. Custody is the one area of the financial services industry
that has remained exempt from the act.
Because most custodians are subsidiaries either of regulated firms or of
banks supervised by the Bank of England, the existing structure could be
modified to improve supervision of the business without having to resort to
legislative change, the review suggests.
However, the SIB says there is a case for developing explicit and higher
standards.
Among the questions raised is whether custodians should be liable for losses
incurred by sub-custodians. The report also lays out the case for greater
supervision of nominee companies - shell companies set up by fund managers
to hold securities on behalf of customers. It notes that some fund managers
have apparently set up such companies to avoid regulation.
The SIB did not take a view on one of the most contentious issues in
custodial practice - whether securities should be held in the name of the
ultimate owner, such as a particular pension scheme, or in the name of the
fund manager's nominee company. Fund managers say the latter cuts
administrative costs.
However, Maxwell pensioners were able to retrieve Pounds 27m of shares
passed to National Westminster Bank as collateral for a personal loan to Mr
Maxwell. They argued that, as the shares were registered in the name of the
scheme, NatWest should have realised the shares did not belong to Mr Maxwell
personally.
Separately, a government advisory panel chaired by Professor Roy Goode is
examining pension fund law. Recommended reforms could include stricter
supervision of the custody business.
</TEXT>
