<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / Fears for skill centres as buy-out prospects recede
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST OF the 35 skillcentres owned by Astra, the failed training
organisation, are in the hands of the receivers and are set to close,
according to the National Union of Civil and Public Servants.
The possibility of a management buy-out for Astra appeared to be receding
last night. The organisation, privatised three years ago when the government
put Pounds 11m into the former Skills Training Agency, suffered from high
overheads and an increasingly competitive funding system.
The Training and Enterprise Councils, which are responsible for delivering
government training schemes in England and Wales, are Astra's biggest
clients. They say the demise of the organisation will make little difference
to either Youth Training or Training for Work, the main training scheme for
the adult unemployed.
Some Tec officials say the shake-out at Astra will be good for the industry.
The one reservation is that the experience of Astra staff in finding
placements for clients could be lost.
It is estimated that Astra, though the biggest training organisation in the
country, accounted for only about 2 per cent of all Tec contracts with
training providers.
'This is at most a minor irritation,' said Mr Andrew Gurr, chief executive
of North Mid Cheshire Tec, which has had a contract with the Astra
skillcentre at Runcorn. 'My in-tray is loaded with offers from other
training providers.'
</TEXT>
