FT  04 AUG 93 / Tories boost fundraising
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LEADING FIGURES in commerce and industry have been enlisted by the
Conservative party to revitalise its fundraising activities.
The party's new board of treasurers includes Mr David Sieff, a director of
retailer Marks and Spencer, Sir Philip Harris, chairman and chief executive
of carpet retailer Carpetright, Mr David Davies, chairman of Johnson
Matthey, the materials technology group, Sir Nigel Mobbs, chairman of
property company Slough Estates, and Mr Anthony Weldon, a director of
financial services group NP Record.
Mr Charles Hambro, the party's senior treasurer, remains chairman of the
board, which also includes two other members of the Tory hierarchy, Sir
Malcolm Chaplin and Mr Tim Smith, MP for Beaconsfield and vice-chairman of
the party.
In the wake of the controversy over the Pounds 400,000 contributed to the
party by Mr Asil Nadir, the former Polly Peck chief who jumped bail and fled
to northern Cyprus, the team of fundraisers will also have a role in vetting
donations.
Sir Norman Fowler, the party chairman, recently wrote to Mr Hambro to 'make
it quite clear' that fundraising must be 'independent of any suggestion of
political influence'.
He reaffirmed yesterday that cuts at Central Office and in the regions had
ensured that the party's spending was no longer in excess of income.
