<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / Bus sell-offs in Scotland rapped
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN WILLMAN, Public Policy Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE privatisation of 10 Scottish bus companies between August 1990 and
October 1991 netted Pounds 103.1m, the National Audit Office said, but this
was Pounds 15m less than the Scottish Office had been advised to expect when
the sell-offs were planned in 1988.
In a report published today the public expenditure watchdog says more could
have been done to maintain the companies' profitability before
privatisation. A deterioration in profits during the pre-sale period reduced
the companies' value to potential purchasers.
The NAO also criticises the Scottish Office for its failure to monitor the
sale costs, which totalled Pounds 2.3m. The Scottish Transport Group, which
owned the companies before privatisation, spent Pounds 1.2m on professional
fees, three times the Scottish Office's estimate.
The Monopolies and Mergers Commission is to investigate the acquisition by
Stagecoach Holdings of Lancaster City Transport. The Department of Trade and
Industry has referred the acquisition on the advice of Sir Bryan Carsberg,
director-general of the Office of Fair Trading, after concern over its
impact on the bus market in the Lancaster and Morecambe area.
Stagecoach has ordered bus bodies worth Pounds 13m, with an option for a
further Pounds 10m, from Walter Alexander of Falkirk, Stirlingshire.
Sale of the Scottish Bus Group. HMSO. Pounds 7.50.
</TEXT>
