<HEADLINE>
FT  04 AUG 93 / Early British Coal sell-off planned: DTI wants company split
before sale to private sector
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INDUSTRY ministers want to privatise the bulk of British Coal by as early as
next July. The sale is likely to break it up into at least two separate
companies.
Ministers also prefer 'trade sales' to other existing companies to a
flotation on the stock exchange, largely because this would be more likely
to lead to the replacement of existing management with private-sector
managers. There are also strong doubts about the public's willingness to buy
shares in such a controversial privatisation.
The industry had expected British Coal to stay in the public sector at least
until early 1995.
Although ministers have yet to decide finally on a break-up, they are
strongly influenced by the privatisations of the gas and electricity
generating industries, where the creation of a monopoly and duopoly
respectively caused considerable controversy.
British Coal will counter that splitting up the industry would weaken its
bargaining power with the electricity generators which are its main
customers.
The Department of Trade and Industry's preferred timetable would entail a
bill being presented to the House of Commons shortly after it re-assembles
in October and a second reading before Christmas. That would open up the
possibility that the bill could be given royal assent and the main parts of
British Coal sold next July.
The timetable has yet to be accepted by the cabinet. But one argument in
favour is that it places as much time as possible between the controversial
sale and the next general election.
Even if the fast-track timetable is approved, large parts of British Coal
would remain in the public sector for months or even years. Ministers have
accepted the need for a residual body, possibly retaining the British Coal
title. This would run some pits while it was determined whether there was a
market for their output.
There may be several pits in that category. Most industry analysts expect
the decline in the market to leave only about 15 of the 30 remaining pits
with a long-term future. But the government could have difficulty closing
the other 15 by the middle of next year, given the public outcry its last
closure plans created.
The residual body would also be in charge of most of the corporation's
Pounds 3bn of liabilities, including those for subsidence and concessionary
coal for former employees.
Ministers' preference for splitting British Coal could allow them to satisfy
the demands of Mining Scotland, an influential lobby group which wants all
interests of the corporation north of the border to be hived off into a
separate company, and has set up a company to buy them.
The bulk of the corporation in England and Wales could easily be divided
into two organisations, one based in the Midlands and the other in
Yorkshire, which the corporation is bringing into being through a
restructuring already under way.
It is possible, however, that the two organisations could be split further.
Isolated mines such as Ellington in Northumberland and Tower in Wales may be
sold off separately, although their future seems less secure than the pits
in the Midlands and Yorkshire.
Mr Robin Cook, the shadow trade and industry secretary, said last night that
Labour would fight any plans to privatise the coal industry.
Gas stations backed, Page 5
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
