FT  03 AUG 93 / International Company News: Elf-Aquitaine expected to
replace chief this week
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR LOIK Le Floch-Prigent, chairman of Elf-Aquitaine, the state-controlled
oil and gas company which is France's largest industrial group, will be
replaced this week, official sources said yesterday.
Mr Philippe Jaffre, chairman of Credit Agricole, one of France's most
powerful financial institutions, is expected to be voted on to the Elf board
today and confirmed as chairman by the government council of ministers
tomorrow.
The move largely reflects political motives. Mr Le Floch-Prigent was
appointed head of Elf by the socialist President Francois Mitterrand in
1989. He has been regarded as vulnerable since the centre-right government
of Mr Edouard Balladur took office in March.
The government is keen to remove a socialist appointee from the head of Elf
because the oil group has been named among the first four companies to be
sold as part of the government's privatisation programme.
The move reflects the practice of replacing the heads of important
state-owned companies following a shift in political power between the left
and the right. So far, however, the government of Mr Balladur has been
restrained in replacing company chiefs. The only other change has been the
replacement of Mr Rene Thomas as head of Banque Nationale de Paris by Mr
Michel Pebereau in May.
The relatively conciliatory approach of the Balladur government is reflected
in the fact that Mr Le Floch-Prigent is expected to be given another
important post.
Official sources said that he would probably take control of Gaz de France,
the state-owned utility.
Mr Jaffre has no previous experience of managing an industrial company. He
worked in the French treasury between 1977 and 1987, and for Mr Rene Monori,
then economy minister, in 1979 and 1980. He was executive chairman at Banque
Stern and was appointed chairman of Credit Agricole in 1988.
A government official said that Mr Jaffre had been selected because of his
management expertise and because the Elf privatisation would be a complex
financial challenge.
The government has indicated that the size of the group - it has an
estimated market value of about FFr100bn (Dollars 16.8bn) - might mean that
it is privatised in tranches.
The government currently holds 51.4 per cent of the shares.
</TEXT>
