<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 93 / France mars Abbey National's gain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GAPPER, Banking Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABBEY National, the home loans and banking group, yesterday reported an 11
per cent rise in interim pre-tax profits to Pounds 301m, against Pounds
270m, helped by rapid growth in wholesale-funded fixed rate mortgages.
Abbey achieved a 31 per cent rise in UK retail profits to Pounds 300m
(Pounds 229m), helped by a lower bad debt charge of Pounds 118m (Pounds
146m). This reflected a fall in house repossessions and in the number of
mortgages in arrears by more than six months.
In France, the bad debt charge rose to Pounds 94m (Pounds 16m) because of
the weak commercial property market. France accounted for most of an Pounds
86m loss in continental Europe and offshore, against a Pounds 9m loss in the
first half of 1992.
The European problems drove up the overall bad debt charge, which includes
loan provisions and suspended interest, by 35 per cent to Pounds 222m
(Pounds 165m).
Abbey raised its share of new mortgage lending to 23.3 per cent of the UK
mortgage market, against 12.4 per cent, by promotion of fixed rate
mortgages. Net lending was Pounds 2bn (Pounds 1.2bn) largely funded by
wholesale funds rather than retail savings.
The group's share of UK retail savings fell from 4.1 to 3.3 per cent as
retail inflows dropped to Pounds 400m (Pounds 700m), and the percentage of
the domestic mortgage book funded by retail savings fell to 80 per cent (86
per cent).
Operating profits before bad debts rose 20 per cent to Pounds 523m (Pounds
435m). Sir Christopher Tugendhat, chairman, said the result was
'encouraging, given that the UK housing market is only just beginning to
emerge from a prolonged recession'.
Sir Christopher said that Abbey believed trading results in France might be
improved by interest rate cuts. He said it was committed to French
operations, although it was 'difficult to make strategic decisions in the
eye of a storm'.
The group has failed to sell its Cornerstone estate agency chain, which it
put up for sale six months ago. Sir Christopher said it was 'negotiating
with other parties' over the chain.
Treasury profits rose 74 per cent to Pounds 66m (Pounds 38m) but the growth
of its treasury balance sheet, which was 48 per cent bigger at Pounds 24.3bn
(Pounds 16.4bn), slowed to 4 per cent over the period as Abbey curtailed
expansion.
Mr Peter Birch, chief executive, said the results reflected an inadequate
return on shareholders' funds of Pounds 3.3bn, but he expected it to improve
as it eliminated 'problem children' such as French commercial lending.
Post-tax earnings fell 5 per cent to Pounds 164m because of a tax charge of
46 per cent, pushed up by unrelieved French losses. The interim dividend was
raised 9 per cent to 4.15p (3.8p), while earnings per share slipped to 12.5
(13.2p).
The share price closed 9p up at 392p.
Lex, Page 14
</TEXT>
