FT  03 AUG 93 / Companies more reluctant to invest
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE reluctance of UK companies to invest in eastern Europe has deepened
during a recession which has led a third of UK companies to reduce their
overall overseas investment, a study by Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the accountants
and management consultants, has found.
A total of 66 per cent of a sample of 100 UK companies from the FT Top 500
expressed an interest in investing in central and eastern Europe. This
compares with with 88 per cent in a similar survey two years ago.
A third said they would not even consider investing in the former Soviet
Union.
