<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 93 / Lloyd's losses 'significantly damage economy'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LOSSES suffered by the Lloyd's of London insurance market have
significantly damaged the domestic economy and balance of payments, a report
published today finds.
Mr Ian Shepherdson, economist with Midland Global Markets Research, writes
in Greenwell Gilt Weekly that Lloyd's losses over the past five years of
more than Pounds 5.5bn are equivalent to the money lost on two or three
'Black Wednesdays'.
'Cumulative losses of this magnitude cannot be ring-fenced from the rest of
the economy,' he says.
Mr Shepherdson estimates that Names - the individuals whose assets support
underwriting - will need to find Pounds 2.3bn to fund the 1990 deficit of
Pounds 2.9bn announced in June in line with Lloyd's three-year accounting
system.
He says the amount is equal to more than 0.5 per cent of UK personal
disposable income and is more than the cost to the personal sector of 1p on
income tax.
He estimates: 'Personal consumption could be reduced by as much as 0.3 per
cent or 0.4 per cent per year as a result of Lloyd's losses.'
The crisis may also affect asset markets, he says. 'It is almost
inconceivable that the losses will have no effect on the property market.'
Lloyd's contribution to the current account has fallen from a surplus of
Pounds 1.4bn in 1987 to a provisional deficit of Pounds 600m last year. Over
the same period the annual current account deficit has risen from Pounds
4.5bn to Pounds 11.5bn.
'The Pounds 2bn swing in Lloyd's performance is equivalent to nearly 30 per
cent of the deterioration in the current account as a whole,' says Mr
Shepherdson.
He concedes that the degree of the impact reflects the shrinkage in the
current account deficit as a whole, but says the position could get worse.
'There is no guarantee that the losses have peaked.'
Lloyd's problems have coincided with a decline in fortunes of the insurance
sector as a whole, with the contribution of insurance companies, brokers and
Lloyd's to the current account falling from more than Pounds 3bn in 1987 to
some Pounds 700m in 1991.
Lloyd's yesterday confirmed that Mr David Bruce had resigned as finance
director to pursue other interests. The appointment of Mr Stephen Hall, who
recently retired from Ernst &amp; Young, is temporary pending a permanent
appointment.
Professor Anthony King, professor of government at the University of Essex,
has been appointed to advise a working party on voting arrangements and
other aspects of Names' representation at the market.
Lloyd's is reviewing its voting system which gives one vote to each Name
irrespective of how much capital they supply.
</TEXT>
