<HEADLINE>
FT  03 AUG 93 / BT 'special offer' calls ruled unfair
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A RECENT British Telecommunications 'special offer' to customers was
discriminatory to competitors and must not be repeated, Oftel, the
telecommunications watchdog, ruled yesterday.
BT will be obliged to agree new rules with Oftel to ensure that future
special offers do not favour its business to the detriment of competitors.
The ruling is a blow to BT, which sees special offers as a way to contain
competition from Mercury and cable TV companies, which are building local
phone networks in conurbations.
Oftel's decision concerns BT's 'Sunday Special' of November and December,
when most long-distance calls after 3pm on Sundays were charged at the local
cheap rate.
Mr Don Cruickshank, Oftel director-general, said the BT tariff for the
Sunday special 'failed to cover the costs of network usage, if those were
assessed on the basis used for other operators connecting to the BT
network'.
Similar behaviour by BT in future 'would have a significant effect on
competition in the telecommunications market' and could not be permitted.
Oftel has not imposed a penalty on BT, but its new rules governing future
special offers are likely to require BT to demonstrate that competitors can
take advantage of the same network tariffs for the use of the BT network as
the company charges itself.
In the longer term, Oftel's recent proposals for full accounting separation
between the 'network' and 'retail' parts of BT's business would make it
harder for BT to discriminate against competitors.
BT said it remained committed to special offers 'as far as they are
permitted by the regulatory regime'.
Mercury said Oftel's decision highlighted 'faultlines' in existing
regulation. 'We don't think tinkering with the existing regime is enough,
but . . . we want to see all competitors free to make exciting offers
provided they do not discriminate,' it said.
</TEXT>
<XX>
